Daily reports about coronavirus disease (COVID-19)

Published 12.03.2020 Updated 27.04.2020

Here is a selection of data from the daily status reports about coronavirus disease (COVID-19) in Norway.

Here is a selection of data from the daily status reports about coronavirus disease (COVID-19) in Norway.

Les på norsk
Share/tip
Facebook Twitter Send by e-mail
Print

Extract from daily COVID-19 report - Monday 27 April 2020

A status report is published every workday at 13:00, based on data from the Norwegian Surveillance System for Communicable Diseases (MSIS), microbiological laboratories, Norwegian Intensive Care Register and Norwegian Syndromic Surveillance System.

  • Total of 7 533 people with confirmed COVID-19, of which 28 were reported yesterday. Updated on the 26.04.2020 at 24:00.
  • 193 deaths have been notified to the NIPH (as of 27.04.2020 at 08:00). 
  • A total of 164 316 have been tested for coronavirus (SARS-CoV-2) (as of 26.04.2020 at 15:00). 
  • Number of people admitted to hospital (figures available from Norwegian Directorate of Health)

Intensive care patients

A total of 211 people in intensive care with confirmed coronavirus (SARS-CoV-2) have been treated in intensive care units, of these, 55 are inpatients. The average age of the 211 confirmed patients is 62 years, and 73 % are male. 30 deaths have been reported.

(figures from Norwegian Intensive Care Register as of 24.04.2020 at 08:00.)

Age and gender 

The average age of cases is 47 years and 49 % are male.

COVID-19 associated deaths

The average age is 83 years, the median age is 85 and 57 % are male. Patients may have died from or with COVID-19.

Geographical distribution by county

R (reproduction number)

The modelling group at the NIPH publish daily reports about the situational analysis and forecasting. The reports include the latest calculation of the R (reproduction number), i.e. how many people infected by an infected person, on average.  

  • Coronavirus modelling at the NIPH - see reports, table 1 in the pdf file shows R.

Laboratory analyses 

The number of laboratory analyses with analyses results are now collected from the National Laboratory database. Analyses results reported on the testing date are copied from laboratories that test for SARS-CoV-2 directly to the database.
